ARTICLE
summary:      The Roman Empire was the post-Republican period of ancient Rome, conventionally dated from 27 BC when Octavian received the title Augustus to AD 476 when the last Western emperor Romulus Augustulus was deposed. At its territorial peak under Trajan (AD 117), it encompassed approximately 5 million square kilometres around the entire Mediterranean basin and extended into Britain, Mesopotamia, and North Africa.
claims:
  - The Empire began in 27 BC when the Roman Senate granted Octavian the title Augustus
  - At peak extent under Trajan (AD 117) it covered approximately 5 million km2
  - The population reached an estimated 55 to 70 million people, roughly one-fifth of the world population
  - The Empire was split administratively into Western and Eastern halves by Diocletian in AD 285
  - The Western Roman Empire fell in AD 476; the Eastern (Byzantine) Empire continued until AD 1453
  - Latin was the official language in the West; Greek dominated the Eastern provinces
  - Roman law, engineering (roads, aqueducts, concrete), and governance profoundly influenced Western civilisation
evidence:     Extensive archaeological record, contemporary Roman historians (Tacitus, Suetonius, Cassius Dio), epigraphic evidence, and numismatic records
limitations:  Population estimates vary widely among historians. Exact boundaries shifted continuously. Dating of the fall is conventionally 476 but decline was gradual.
methodology:  Encyclopedic synthesis of classical history and archaeology
---
NOTES
The Pax Romana (27 BC — AD 180) was a period of relative peace and stability that facilitated trade, cultural exchange, and infrastructure development across the empire. The Roman road network spanned over 400,000 km. Roman concrete (opus caementicium) enabled architectural feats like the Pantheon dome, which remains the world's largest unreinforced concrete dome.